#include <stdio.h>

void findCommon(int arr1[], int arr2[], int m, int n, int *result) {
    int i = 0, j = 0;
    while (i < m && j < n) {
        if (arr1[i] < arr2[j])
            i++;
        else if (arr2[j] < arr1[i])
            j++;
        else {
            *result = arr2[j];
            printf("Common elements: %d\n", *result);
            i++;
            j++;
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int arr1[] = {1, 5, 10, 20, 40, 80};
    int arr2[] = {6, 7, 20, 80, 100};
    int m = sizeof(arr1) / sizeof(arr1[0]);
    int n = sizeof(arr2) / sizeof(arr2[0]);
    int result;
    findCommon(arr1, arr2, m, n, &result);
    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we initialize two pointers `i` and `j` to 0. We then enter a loop that continues until one of the arrays is exhausted. Inside the loop, we compare the current elements of the arrays. If `arr1[i]` is less than `arr2[j]`, we increment `i`. If `arr2[j]` is less than `arr1[i]`, we increment `j`. If they are equal, we print the common element and increment both `i` and `j`.

The `findCommon` function takes four parameters: the two input arrays, their sizes, and a pointer to an integer that stores the common element. The `main` function demonstrates how to use `findCommon`. Note that the `result` variable is passed by address, so any changes made to it within `findCommon` are visible in `main`.
